Lecture 5 - Probability Distribution

Probability Distribution

Function Template Purpose Binomial Normal
dxxx() Returns the density (height of PMF/PDF) dbinom(k, n, p) dnorm(x, mean, sd)
pxxx() Returns cumulative probability, P(X<=x) pbinom(k, n, p) pnorm(q, mean, sd)
qxxx() Returns the quantile (x-coordinate) from a given CDF probability qbinom(k, n, p) qnorm(p, mean, sd)
rxxx() Generate N random numbers from distribution rbinom(N, n, p) rnorm(N, mean, sd)
Example Meaning Output
dbinom(2, 5, 0.25) Prob of obtaining 2 successes in 5 trials, where p=0.25 0.263
pbinom(2, 5, 0.25) Prob of obtaining \(\leq\) 2 successes in 5 trials, where p=0.25 0.896
qbinom(0.896, 5, 0.25) Smallest value x where F(x) \(\geq\) 0.896 2
rbinom(2, 5, 0.25) Generate 2 k values from this binomial dist. 2 from {0,1,2,3,4}

Binomial

Use dbinom() to get the PMF values

p = 0.25
n = 10

#Visualize  the PMF
barplot(dbinom(0:10,n,p),xlab="# of success",ylab="Probability") #出現0:10次成功的機率

map_dbl(0:10, dbinom, n,p) #apply a function to each element of a vector and return a vector
data.pmf <- tibble(k = 0:n, prob = map_dbl(0:n, dbinom, n, p))        

#Visualize PMF using example X~B(10, 0.25)
ggplot(data.pmf, aes(x = k, y=prob))+ 
  geom_bar( stat="identity" ) +
  ggtitle("PMF for X~B(10, 0.25)") +
  ylab("Probability") +
  xlab("number of success")  #(or scale_x_continuous(name = "number of success", breaks = 0:10))

###Visualize CDF using example X~B(10, 0.25)
## Step One: Generate random numbers from the distribution of interest. Here, we generate 5000

data.cdf <- tibble(x = rbinom(5000, 10, 0.25))

## Step Two: plot with stat_ecdf()
ggplot(data.cdf, aes(x = x)) + 
    stat_ecdf() + 
  scale_x_continuous(name = "number of success", breaks = 0:10) +
  ylab("Cumulative Probability") + 
  ggtitle("CDF for X~B(10, 0.25)")

Normal

pnorm(1.96,lower.tail = F) #calculating the area to the right of 1.96.
qnorm(0.05,lower.tail = F) #get the critical value 

#Visualize PDF using example X~N(2, 4) (i.e. mean=2, variance=4)
## Step One: Create a data frame giving the x-axis range. +/- 3sd is usually ok
range.pdf <- tibble(x = c(2 - 6, 2 + 6))

## Step Two: plot with stat_function
ggplot(range.pdf, aes(x = x)) + 
  stat_function(fun = dnorm, args = list(mean = 2, sd=sqrt(4) )) + 
  xlab("X") + 
  ylab("Probability") + 
  ggtitle("PDF for X~N(2, 4)")

##Visualize CDF using example X~N(2, 4)
data.cdf <- tibble(x = rnorm(10000, 2, 4))
ggplot(data.cdf, aes(x=x)) + stat_ecdf() +  ggtitle("CDF for X~N(2, 4)")

x = rnorm(10000, 2, 4)
hist(x) #distribution

d=density(x) #kernel density
plot(d)
